sec.p:
Taking NWs to a definite position sideways and connecting them to the metal electrodes is the main hurdle. The prevalent transfer method primarily has two phases [48, 49]. For the first phase, NWs are distanced from growth substrate and then a volatile solvent is used to disperse them. Next, a single drop of the solvent is cast on the target substrate. For the second phase, lithography helps in determining the electrode windows, followed by metal deposition and lift-off techniques. But in this case NWs are arbitrarily arrayed on the substrate. Obtaining a device with NWs that connect to metal contacts at both ends takes a lot of time. In addition, manufacturing a device with few aligned NWs through the above method is quite challenging. A few methods and certain equipment of assembly of NWs have been reported in detail [34, 50–53]. Manufacture of devices with horizontally arrayed silicon NW has been reported such as [54]:
• a SiO2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\mathrm{SiO}}_{2}$$\end{document} substrate prepared by thermal oxidization of an n-type wafer is utilized and spin-coating of photoresist is done;
• perpendicular pressing of the etched substrate on intended substrate, using metal-assisted chemical etching (MACE) method [55];
• silicon NWs are transported on intended substrate;
• spin-coating of photoresist’s second layer was performed;
• through photolithography and lift-off processes, multi-wire devices are properly manufactured.

